<font color="#FF0000">VISITING THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 29 17:40:02 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
  Maya Lin's works, if you think about it - the Vietnam Veteran's Memorial, the Civil Rights sculpture, the Yale Women's sculpture - are transcendent of their specific American historical subject matter and attains a broader spatial representation of key modern human experiences, no doubt informed by philosophical insights developed long before these experiences.Circularity in the experience of pain and loss, or in the experiences of large-scale madness or injustice or inequality, is but one example. Coming to terms with what we have created and done. Celebrating the human spirit in spite of its terrible deeds. I am glad that she is a creature of modernity but not for modernity, but rather for humanity.<br><br>
  As to my personal reaction to the VVM when I first visited it with my five-year-old son, I felt it was a good beginning, not a finished coming to terms with that war and the pain it caused. When my son asked me if the names were of all those who died in that war, I answered: &quot;No, son; for that we would need to inscribe the four walls of the Washington Monument.&quot; He turned and looked at the WM, and amazed, turned to me and asked: &quot;So, who are these names?&quot; &quot;These,&quot; I said, &quot;are merely the names of the AMERICANS who died in that war...&quot; <br><br>
  Although Maya Lin helped Americans come to terms with their own pain, I wondered then why it was that Americans and many others from past great powers had not been able to see beyond their own pain and into the pain of others, especially the pain they may have caused to others.Maya Lin's memorial is purely American, but it points the way to the kind of thoughts and feelings my son and I had when we visited it, feeling for others.
